result.execSummary:
The defendant Ashley Moss was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ashley Moss in court with attorney Eduardo M. Borda.  Lindsey Anderson appears under the student practice rule supervised by Molly M Schmidt for Abbey DeSiato for the State of Wisconsin.
Sentencing proceeded. Statements by all parties.
AS to count 2:   The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 10 days in the House of Correction, concurrent with count 1 in 14CM3506, with credit for 10 days time served.    The court orders defendant to pay all applicable costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, DNA surcharge as a condition of probation as imposed in counts 1 and 3 and failure to do so will result in entry of civil judgment.
AS to count 1 and 3:  
Count 1:  The court sentenced the defendant to serve 90 days in the House of Correction, with credit for 0 days time served. 
Count 3:  The court sentenced the defendant to serve 7 months in the House of Correction, consecutive to count 1.
The court STAYED sentences and placed defendant on probation with the WI Department of Corrections for a period of 24 months concurrent.
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
-Serve 60 days in the House of Correction, each count consecutive STAYED pending a review on 3-11-2016 at 1:15pm in Branch 38.
-Mental health evaluation and take all prescribed medication(s), and/or treatment deemed appropriate.
-AODA and recommended treatment including random urine screens/Maintain ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
-Parenting classes.
-Attend and successfully complete treatment and counseling programs as deemed appropriate by agent.
-NO CONTACT with the victim, UNLESS requested by victim and then only with prior approval of agent or the court or Children's court.  FOLLOW ALL CHILDREN'S COURT ORDERS.

Defendant Ashley Moss in court with attorney Eduardo M. Borda.  Lindsey Anderson, student intern, appears under the student practice rule supervised by Abbey Marie DeSiato for the State of Wisconsin.
  On motion of the State, Court ordered count 1 amended to DISORDERLY CONDUCT, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 947.01(1), a Class B misdemeanor.
As to all three counts:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
Case is adjourned to 11-10-2015 at 8:15 for sentencing.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for November 10, 2015 at 08:15 am.
Plea date scheduled for October 27, 2015 at 08:15 am.
